b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe48398.htm)  [Next](sbe48400.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n15\\. And on account of the term 'Self.'\n\nThat this is so further follows from the fact that in the clause 'different\nfrom this is the inner Self consisting of bliss' the term 'Self is used. For\nas the Self cannot really possess a head, wings, and tail, its having joy for\nits head, and so on, can only be meant in a metaphorical sense, for the sake\nof easier comprehension.--But, in the preceding sections, the term _Self_ had\nbeen applied to what is _not_ of the nature of Self--the text speaking of the\nSelf of breath, the Self of mind, and so on; how then are we able to determine\nthat in the phrase 'the Self of bliss' the term\n\np. 640\n\n[paragraph continues] Self denotes a true _Self_?--To this the next Sutra\nreplies.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: 16. There is reference to the Self, as in other\nplaces...](sbe48400.htm)\n\n"